@node Introduction

Here is yet another random wb picture program.  I wrote this because not one of the 4
other programs I downloaded off Aminet worked how I wanted them too, some of them simply
copied a random picture to another file which you picked as your backdrop, hardly the
most efficient way.

My program creates a new wbpattern.prefs in ENV: with a random backdrop picked from a
list of files and then quits.  Only the filename is altered, any options set (e.g. with
FastWBPattern) won`t be touched.  I did think of just reading a directory for the files
as it would be easier to maintain than a file list, but it would slow down bootup,
particularly if you had a lot of files.  It is much faster to read a 10k+ file than it is to
get a directory containing the equivalent amount of entries.

Since this program was coded in assembler, it is much smaller than similar programs and
it also supports changing of the backdrop at any time - just run the program again.
@endnode
@node "Installation and Usage"

Copy the program (and icon) to wherever (recommended=sys:system).

Make sure the WBPattern prefs for Workbench is set to picture, you shouldn't need to
set a filename.  You will need to set precision and any other options as they won't
be set (or changed) by this program.

Add it to the startup-sequence after the line "copy envarc: env:sys..." and/or after MCP
(no arguments needed).  It is possible to put it in the WBStartup drawer, but this is
not recommended since it will most likely result in the background being loaded twice.

Make a list by running the supplied MakeList script (list is saved as S:WBPicList)
The script recurses into sub-directories and it is alphabetically sorted so that you
can find filenames easier (i.e. for removal).  Thanks to Goran Cengic for help with this.

Edit the list with a text editor (if necessary) to remove any pics you don`t want to see.
Each filename should be on a seperate line (no empty lines between filenames).

A new list can be made at any time (no reboot necessary) and if you get sick of
the backdrop simply run the program again from it's icon and workbench will detect the
change to the prefs file and load the new backdrop.

Notes:

I have an entry in the tools menu which gets rid of the backdrop in order to save memory.
To do this I made a prefs file which was set to a plain pattern and saved it in presets.
When I used my program to change from this prefs back to a random picture I got badly
dithered pics and sometimes the colours were wrong (on gfx board).
So if you do the same and have this problem ensure that in the preset file the precision
is set correctly.  You cannot alter the precision if "Type" is set to pattern, so change
it to picture, set precision, set back to pattern and save.

@endnode
@node "History and Future"

1.0	First release

1.1	Fixed problem with changing backdrops caused by file format assumptions.
	Improved and optimised random number routine (~50% smaller).
	Name changed to RandyPic upon finding another program with the name of
	RandomPic in a different dir on Aminet.

1.2	Added Makelist script (thanks to Goran Cengic) which just missed
	previous release.  More optimisations.
	Version not uploaded to Aminet due to problem with window patterns.

1.3	More optimisations.
	Fixed problems with window patterns.  Due to a few more assumptions the
	settings for "pattern" were being ignored and all you got was a plain
	gray background.

1.4	Lots more optimisations.
	Fixed Freemem() bug - forgot to pass amount of mem to free up (Doh!)
	Should be the last bug - for now ;-)

Here are some possible additions:

Add support for random window patterns (pretty easy to do).
Only problem is most backdrop pics are not suitable for windows, so a seperate
list would probably be needed.

Reading of dir instead of list file will not happen now since another program
called RandWBpix (or something like that) on Aminet works that way.

More Optimisations


